(65, 1, 1, 60, 1, 5, 5, 'preserved in Jesus Christ', 'Preservation by God''s Power', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being preserved or kept by God. Jude mentions being ''preserved in Jesus Christ,'' while Peter states that believers are ''kept by the power of God.'' This connection highlights the assurance of divine protection for the faithful.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 1, 52, 5, 23, 23, 'sanctified by God the Father', 'Sanctification and Preservation', 'Both passages emphasize the concepts of sanctification and preservation. Jude mentions being ''sanctified by God'' and ''preserved in Jesus Christ,'' while 1 Thessalonians speaks of being ''sanctify you wholly'' and ''preserved blameless.''', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 1, 60, 2, 9, 9, 'called', 'Called and Chosen People', 'This connection highlights the theme of being ''called'' by God. Both passages emphasize the identity of believers as sanctified and chosen, reflecting their special status in relation to God.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 1, 43, 14, 22, 22, 'called', 'Connection of Believers and Manifestation', 'This connection highlights the theme of those called and sanctified by God, as seen in Jude, and the inquiry of Judas about how Jesus will reveal himself to believers. Both passages emphasize the relationship between Jesus and his followers, suggesting a distinct connection in their experiences of divine revelation.', 'theme', 0.349, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 1, 43, 17, 15, 15, 'preserved in Jesus Christ', 'Preservation from Evil', 'This connection highlights the theme of being preserved by God. Jude mentions being ''preserved in Jesus Christ,'' while John emphasizes keeping from evil, suggesting divine protection for the sanctified.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 1, 45, 1, 1, 1, 'servant of Jesus Christ', 'Servants of Jesus Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the authors as ''servants of Jesus Christ.'' This connection highlights their shared identity and mission in the early Christian community.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 1, 55, 1, 9, 9, 'called', 'Calling and Purpose in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''called.'' Jude mentions those ''called'' by God, while 2 Timothy speaks of a ''holy calling'' given by God. This connection highlights the divine initiative in the calling of believers.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 2, 61, 1, 2, 2, 'peace, and love, be multiplied', 'Multiplication of Grace and Peace', 'Both passages emphasize the multiplication of peace, with Jude mentioning ''peace'' and 2 Peter referring to ''grace and peace.'' This connection highlights a shared theme of divine blessings being increased in the lives of believers.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 2, 60, 1, 2, 2, NULL, 'Multiplication of Grace and Peace', 'Both passages emphasize the multiplication of grace and peace to believers. Jude 1:2 mentions ''peace'' and ''love,'' while 1 Peter 1:2 includes ''grace'' and ''peace,'' highlighting a shared theme of divine blessings.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 2, 66, 1, 4, 6, 'peace', 'Connection of Mercy and Peace', 'Both passages emphasize the themes of mercy and peace. Jude 1:2 mentions ''mercy'' and ''peace,'' while Revelation 1:4 highlights ''grace'' and ''peace,'' suggesting a continuity in the blessings offered to believers.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 2, 45, 1, 7, 7, 'peace', 'Connection of Grace and Peace', 'Both passages emphasize the themes of mercy and peace, highlighting the importance of these qualities in the lives of believers. Jude''s greeting of ''mercy'' and ''peace'' parallels Paul''s greeting of ''grace'' and ''peace'', suggesting a shared emphasis on divine favor and tranquility.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 3, 54, 6, 12, 12, 'earnestly contend for the faith', 'Contending for the Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of actively engaging in the faith. Jude encourages believers to ''earnestly contend for the faith,'' while Timothy is urged to ''fight the good fight of faith.''', 'theme', 0.503, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 3, 50, 1, 27, 27, 'for the faith', 'Striving for the Faith', 'This connection highlights the call to ''contend for the faith'' in Jude and the encouragement to ''striving together for the faith'' in Philippians. Both passages emphasize the importance of unity and perseverance in maintaining the faith among believers.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 3, 65, 1, 20, 20, 'faith which was once delivered', 'Faith and Spiritual Growth', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of faith. Jude 1:3 encourages believers to ''contend for the faith,'' while Jude 1:20 speaks of ''building up yourselves on your most holy faith.'' This connection highlights the active role believers must take in nurturing their faith.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 3, 55, 1, 13, 13, 'earnestly contend for the faith', 'Contending for Sound Doctrine', 'This connection highlights the importance of holding fast to the faith and sound words. Both passages emphasize the need for believers to actively preserve and defend the teachings they have received.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 3, 56, 1, 4, 4, 'common salvation', 'Common Faith Emphasis', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''common faith'' among believers. Jude encourages contending for this faith, while Titus is addressed as a son in the context of this shared belief.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 3, 55, 4, 7, 8, 'earnestly contend for the faith', 'Contending for the Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of fighting for faith. Both passages emphasize the importance of maintaining faith and the rewards for those who do so.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 3, 66, 12, 11, 11, 'earnestly contend for the faith', 'Faith and Overcoming Challenges', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of faith and perseverance in the face of adversity. Jude encourages believers to ''earnestly contend for the faith,'' while Revelation highlights overcoming through ''the blood of the Lamb'' and testimony.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 4, 61, 2, 1, 3, 'denying the only Lord God', 'Connection of False Teachers', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of false teachers who deny the Lord. They warn of the destructive consequences of their actions and the corruption of the truth. This connection highlights a shared concern for the integrity of faith.', 'theme', 0.538, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 4, 48, 2, 4, 4, 'crept in unawares', 'Connection of False Brethren', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of individuals who infiltrate the community unnoticed, promoting false teachings. They highlight the danger these ''ungodly men'' and ''false brethren'' pose to the faith and liberty of believers.', 'theme', 0.517, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 4, 61, 2, 10, 10, 'ungodly men, turning the grace', 'Connection of Ungodliness and Presumption', 'Both passages emphasize the behavior of ungodly men who indulge in sinful desires. Jude highlights those turning grace into lasciviousness, while Peter describes those walking after the flesh and despising authority.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 4, 56, 1, 15, 16, 'denying the only Lord God', 'Connection of Defilement and Denial', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of individuals who profess knowledge of God yet deny Him through their actions. Jude speaks of ungodly men who turn grace into lasciviousness, while Titus describes those whose minds and consciences are defiled, denying God through their works.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 4, 60, 2, 16, 16, 'turning the grace of our God into lasciviousness', 'Connection of Liberty and Lasciviousness', 'This connection highlights the misuse of freedom. Jude warns against turning grace into lasciviousness, while Peter advises against using liberty for maliciousness.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 4, 62, 2, 22, 22, 'denying the only Lord God', 'Denial of Christ Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the denial of Jesus Christ, linking those who reject Him to ungodliness. Jude warns against those who deny the Lord, while 1 John identifies such deniers as antichrist.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 4, 60, 2, 8, 8, 'ordained to this condemnation', 'Connection of Appointments in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize individuals who are appointed for condemnation or disobedience. Jude speaks of those ordained to condemnation, while Peter refers to those who were appointed to stumble. This connection highlights a theme of divine appointment related to judgment.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 5, 4, 26, 64, 65, 'destroyed them that believed not', 'Judgment of Unbelievers', 'Both passages emphasize the consequence of unbelief among the Israelites. Jude recalls how the Lord destroyed those who did not believe after their deliverance from Egypt, while Numbers recounts that none of those numbered in the wilderness survived due to their lack of faith.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 5, 46, 10, 1, 12, 'destroyed them that believed not', 'Judgment of Unbelievers', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of unbelief among the Israelites after their deliverance from Egypt. Jude 1:5 mentions the destruction of those who believed not, while 1 Corinthians 10:5 highlights that God was not well pleased with many of them, leading to their overthrow in the wilderness.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 5, 19, 106, 26, 26, 'destroyed them that believed not', 'Judgment in the Wilderness', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences faced by the Israelites after their deliverance from Egypt. Jude 1:5 refers to their destruction due to unbelief, while Psalms 106:26 describes God''s action to overthrow them in the wilderness.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 5, 4, 14, 22, 37, 'destroyed them that believed not', 'Judgment for Unbelief', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of unbelief among the Israelites after their deliverance from Egypt. Jude 1:5 recalls the destruction of those who did not believe, which is illustrated in Numbers 14:22-37 through God''s judgment on the faithless generation.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 5, 5, 2, 15, 16, 'destroyed them that believed not', 'Destruction of Unbelievers', 'Both passages emphasize the destruction of those who did not believe. Jude recalls the Lord''s action against the unbelieving Israelites after their exodus, paralleling Deuteronomy''s account of the Lord''s hand against them until they were consumed.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 5, 61, 3, 1, 1, 'put you in remembrance', 'Remembrance of Past Events', 'This connection highlights the theme of remembrance in both passages. Jude emphasizes recalling the Lord''s past actions, while 2 Peter also focuses on stirring up minds by way of remembrance.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 6, 61, 2, 4, 4, NULL, 'Connection of Angels and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the fate of angels that sinned, specifically mentioning their being cast into chains of darkness and reserved for judgment. This connection highlights a shared theme of divine judgment against rebellious angels.', 'theme', 0.5309999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 6, 40, 25, 41, 41, 'angels which kept not their first estate', 'Angels and Eternal Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment for angels. Both passages emphasize the consequences for those who rebel, with Jude referencing angels in chains and Matthew mentioning fire prepared for the devil and his angels.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 6, 49, 6, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Spiritual Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual beings and their roles. Jude 1:6 refers to angels in chains, while Ephesians 6:12 mentions rulers of darkness, indicating a struggle against spiritual forces.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 6, 40, 8, 29, 29, 'reserved in everlasting chains', 'Angelic Judgment and Torment', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment for angels. Jude speaks of angels reserved in chains until judgment, while Matthew mentions demons fearing torment before the appointed time.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 6, 58, 10, 27, 27, 'judgment', 'Judgment and Indignation Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment present in both passages. Jude speaks of angels reserved for judgment, while Hebrews anticipates a fearful judgment for adversaries.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 6, 66, 20, 10, 10, 'reserved in everlasting chains', 'Judgment of the Fallen Angels', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment for those who rebel against God. Both passages refer to beings being reserved for punishment, emphasizing the consequences of their actions.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 6, 43, 8, 44, 44, NULL, 'Connection of Rebellion and Deceit', 'This connection highlights the theme of rebellion against God. Jude 1:6 speaks of angels who left their own habitation, paralleling John 8:44''s depiction of the devil, who did not abide in the truth.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 7, 5, 29, 23, 23, 'Sodom and Gomorrha, and the cities about them', 'Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah', 'Both passages emphasize the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah as a consequence of divine wrath. Jude references their fate as an example of suffering, while Deuteronomy describes the land''s desolation after their overthrow.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 7, 45, 1, 26, 27, 'suffering the vengeance of eternal fire', 'Connection of Divine Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of sexual immorality and unnatural relations. Jude references Sodom and Gomorrha as examples of divine judgment, while Romans describes similar behaviors leading to God''s abandonment.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 7, 61, 2, 6, 6, NULL, 'Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrha', 'Both passages emphasize the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrha as a warning against ungodliness. They highlight the cities'' fate as an example for those who live in a similar manner.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 7, 1, 18, 20, 20, NULL, 'Sin and Judgment in Sodom', 'Both passages emphasize the grievous nature of sin in Sodom and Gomorrah, highlighting their ultimate judgment. Jude refers to their suffering as an example of divine vengeance, while Genesis notes the great cry due to their grievous sin.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 7, 1, 19, 24, 26, 'suffering the vengeance of eternal fire', 'Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah', 'Both passages emphasize the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah due to their sinful actions. Jude references their suffering as an example of divine judgment, paralleling the account of their destruction in Genesis.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 7, 24, 50, 40, 40, 'Even as Sodom and Gomorrha', 'Destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah', 'Both passages emphasize the overthrow of Sodom and Gomorrah as a divine judgment. They illustrate the consequences of immorality and serve as a warning against similar behaviors.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 7, 42, 17, 29, 29, 'suffering the vengeance of eternal fire', 'Destruction of Sodom Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the destruction of Sodom and its consequences. Jude references Sodom''s example of suffering, while Luke describes the day of its destruction.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 8, 58, 13, 17, 17, 'despise dominion', 'Authority and Rebellion', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority and submission. Jude warns against those who ''despise dominion,'' while Hebrews encourages obedience to those in authority.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 8, 61, 2, 10, 12, 'despise dominion', 'Connection of Despising Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of despising authority, as seen in the phrases ''despise dominion'' and ''despise government.'' This connection highlights a shared condemnation of those who speak evil of dignities.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 8, 2, 22, 28, 28, 'speak evil of dignities', 'Reviling Authority and Dignity', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of respecting authority figures. Jude warns against speaking evil of dignities, paralleling Exodus'' command to not revile rulers.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 8, 54, 1, 10, 10, 'defile the flesh', 'Connection of Moral Defilement', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of moral defilement, with Jude referencing those who ''defile the flesh'' and 1 Timothy listing ''whoremongers'' and those who ''defile themselves with mankind.'' This connection highlights a shared concern for maintaining sound doctrine against immoral behaviors.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 8, 60, 2, 17, 17, 'despise dominion', 'Respect for Authority', 'This connection highlights the contrast between those who ''despise dominion'' in Jude and the call to ''honour the king'' in 1 Peter. Both passages emphasize the importance of recognizing and respecting authority figures.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 8, 4, 16, 3, 3, 'speak evil of dignities', 'Rebellion Against Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the defiance against established leadership. Jude describes individuals who ''speak evil of dignities,'' paralleling the rebellion of Korah''s followers against Moses and Aaron in Numbers.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 8, 21, 10, 20, 20, 'speak evil of dignities', 'Authority and Speech', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of respecting authority and the consequences of speaking against it. Jude warns against speaking evil of dignities, while Ecclesiastes advises against cursing the king, highlighting the potential repercussions of such actions.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 9, 38, 3, 2, 2, 'The Lord rebuke thee', 'Rebuke of Satan Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase, ''The Lord rebuke thee,'' highlighting a shared theme of divine authority in confronting Satan. This connection illustrates the role of God in rebuking evil.', 'theme', 0.524, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 9, 61, 2, 11, 11, 'railing accusation', 'Angelic Authority and Accusation', 'Both passages emphasize the restraint of angels in making accusations. Jude highlights Michael''s refusal to bring a railing accusation, while 2 Peter notes that angels do not bring such accusations before the Lord.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 9, 5, 34, 6, 6, 'the body of Moses', 'Michael and Moses'' Burial', 'This connection highlights the dispute over Moses'' body, as mentioned in Jude, and the mysterious burial of Moses in Deuteronomy. Both passages emphasize the significance of Moses'' body and its unknown location.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 9, 27, 12, 1, 1, 'Michael the archangel', 'Michael''s Role in Spiritual Warfare', 'This connection highlights Michael''s role as an archangel in spiritual conflict. Both passages emphasize his protective nature over God''s people during times of trouble.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 9, 66, 12, 7, 7, 'Michael the archangel', 'Michael''s Role in Spiritual Warfare', 'This connection highlights Michael''s role as an archangel engaged in spiritual conflict. Both passages depict Michael contending against the forces of evil, emphasizing his authority and the cosmic battle between good and evil.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 9, 27, 10, 21, 21, NULL, 'Connection of Michael the Archangel', 'This connection highlights the role of Michael as an archangel and protector. Both passages emphasize Michael''s authority and significance in spiritual matters.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 9, 52, 4, 16, 16, NULL, 'Connection of Archangel References', 'This connection highlights the role of the archangel in both passages. Michael the archangel contends with the devil in Jude, while 1 Thessalonians mentions the voice of the archangel at the resurrection.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 10, 61, 2, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Brute Beasts', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''natural brute beasts'' and their corrupt understanding. This connection highlights the shared theme of ignorance and self-destruction among those who speak evil of what they do not comprehend.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 10, 45, 1, 21, 22, 'speak evil of those things which they know not', 'Connection of Foolishness and Ignorance', 'This connection highlights the theme of ignorance leading to corruption and foolishness. Both passages emphasize how those who do not acknowledge God or understand spiritual truths become corrupt and darkened in their understanding.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 11, 61, 2, 15, 15, 'error of Balaam for reward', 'Connection of Balaam''s Error', 'Both passages emphasize the error of Balaam, highlighting his pursuit of unrighteous gain. This connection illustrates a shared theme of straying from the right path for personal reward.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 11, 62, 3, 12, 12, 'the way of Cain', 'Connection Between Cain''s Actions', 'Both passages emphasize the wickedness of Cain, highlighting his evil actions in contrast to his brother''s righteousness. Jude warns against following Cain''s path, while 1 John identifies Cain as ''of that wicked one'' for his murderous act.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 11, 66, 2, 14, 14, 'error of Balaam for reward', 'Connection of Balaam''s Doctrine', 'Both passages emphasize the error of Balaam, highlighting the dangers of leading others into sin for personal gain. Jude warns against those who follow this path, while Revelation addresses those who hold to Balaam''s teachings, specifically regarding idolatry and immorality.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 11, 1, 4, 3, 14, 'the way of Cain', 'Connection of Cain''s Actions', 'This connection highlights the consequences of Cain''s actions, as Jude references those who have ''gone in the way of Cain.'' Both passages emphasize the themes of wrongdoing and the resulting judgment from God.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 11, 4, 16, 1, 35, 'gainsaying of Core', 'Rebellion Against God''s Authority', 'Both passages emphasize rebellion against divinely appointed leadership. Jude references the ''gainsaying of Core,'' which directly relates to Korah''s challenge against Moses and Aaron in Numbers, illustrating the consequences of such defiance.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 11, 4, 26, 9, 10, 'gainsaying of Core', 'Connection of Rebellion and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize rebellion against God and its consequences. Jude references the ''gainsaying of Core,'' linking to the rebellion of Dathan and Abiram in Numbers, who opposed Moses and faced divine judgment.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 11, 58, 11, 4, 4, 'the way of Cain', 'Connection of Cain and Abel', 'This connection highlights the contrasting outcomes of Cain and Abel''s sacrifices. Jude references the ''way of Cain,'' which emphasizes Cain''s error, while Hebrews commends Abel''s faith and righteousness in his offering.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 12, 40, 15, 13, 13, 'plucked up by the roots', 'Connection of Fruit and Roots', 'Both passages emphasize the fate of plants that are not fruitful or rooted properly. Jude describes trees without fruit, while Matthew states that plants not planted by God will be rooted up.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 12, 61, 2, 17, 20, 'clouds they are without water', 'Connection of Empty Promises', 'Both passages emphasize the imagery of ''wells without water'' and ''clouds...without water,'' highlighting the futility of false teachers. They depict these figures as alluring yet ultimately empty, leading others into bondage and corruption.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 12, 26, 34, 8, 8, NULL, 'Self-Serving Shepherds', 'Both passages emphasize the failure of leaders to care for their flock, highlighting how they feed themselves rather than the people. Jude describes individuals who are without fear and without fruit, paralleling Ezekiel''s shepherds who neglect their duty.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 12, 20, 25, 14, 14, 'clouds they are without water', 'Connection of Empty Promises', 'Both passages emphasize the imagery of clouds and wind without rain, highlighting the futility of false promises. This connection illustrates the idea of being unproductive and deceptive in their offerings.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 12, 50, 3, 19, 19, 'feeding themselves without fear', 'Connection of Spiritual Deception', 'This connection highlights the theme of false teachers who prioritize earthly desires over spiritual truth. Both passages emphasize the consequences of such behavior, depicting them as ultimately leading to destruction and spiritual barrenness.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 12, 49, 4, 14, 14, 'carried about of winds', 'Connection of Deception and Instability', 'Both passages emphasize being ''carried about'' by deceptive influences. Jude warns against those who are ''clouds...without water,'' while Ephesians cautions against being ''tossed to and fro'' by false teachings. This connection highlights the danger of instability in faith.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 12, 43, 15, 4, 6, 'without fruit, twice dead', 'Fruitfulness and Withering', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of bearing fruit. Jude describes trees without fruit as ''twice dead,'' while John warns that branches not abiding in the vine wither and are burned. This connection highlights the consequences of spiritual barrenness.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 13, 61, 2, 17, 17, 'darkness for ever', 'Imagery of Darkness and Despair', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of darkness reserved for the wicked. Jude mentions ''the blackness of darkness for ever,'' while 2 Peter refers to ''the mist of darkness is reserved for ever.'' This connection highlights a shared imagery of judgment and hopelessness.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(65, 1, 13, 50, 3, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Shame and Destruction', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of shame associated with destruction. Jude describes ''foaming out their own shame,'' while Philippians mentions ''whose glory is in their shame,'' linking the concepts of shame and negative outcomes.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
